rt, Dye Among Honorees At Awards Banquet - GoDucks.com - The University of Oregon Official Athletics Web Site|website=GoDucks.com - The University of Oregon Official Athletics Web Site}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n* Google Cloud Academic All America 1st Team Member of the Year <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academicallamerica.com/news/2018/12/10/2018-google-cloud-academic-all-america-ncaa-division-i-football-team-announced.aspx|title=2018 Google Cloud Academic All-America\u00ae NCAA Division I Football Team Announced|website=academicallamerica.com}}</ref>\n* Pac-12 All-Academic 1st team<ref name=\"2018 all-academic\" />\n* Skeie's Award (Oregon Team Award - Most Valuable Player) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goducks.com/news/2018/11/26/football-herbert-amadi-share-team-mvp-award.aspx|title=Herbert, Amadi Share Team MVP Award|website=University of Oregon Athletics}}</ref>\n\n====2019====\n* Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Week (Pac-12 Coaches) \u2013 October 21, 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/videos/oregons-justin-herbert-named-pac-12-offensive-player-week-after-4-touchdown-performance|title=Oregon's Justin Herbert named Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Week after 4-touchdown performance|website=Pac-12}}</ref>\n* [[William V. Campbell Trophy]]{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====2020====\n*[[2020 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] Offensive MVP{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 6\u00bc\n|       weight = 236\n|         dash = 4.68\n|    ten split =\n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle = 4.46\n|   cone drill = 7.06\n|     vertical = 35.5\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 3\n|        bench =\n|     arm span = 32\u215e\n|    hand span = 10\n|    wonderlic =\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/justin-herbert?id=32194845-5203-1169-a699-ce41d700202a |title=Justin Herbert Combine Profile |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://goducks.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8471 Oregon Ducks bio]\n\n{{Oregon Ducks quarterback navbox}}\n{{Football Academic All-America of the Year}}\n{{William V. Campbell Trophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herbert, Justin}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Oregon]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Justin Herbert\n| image               = Justin_Herbert.png\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| number              = --\n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1998|3|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Eugene, Oregon]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 6\n| weight_lb           = 237\n| high_school         = [[Sheldon High School (Oregon)|Sheldon]] ([[Eugene, Oregon]])\n| college             = [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| undraftedyear       = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n* 1st Team Academic All American (2017)\n* [[William V. Campbell Trophy]] (2019)\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Justin Herbert\n|school=Oregon Ducks\n|currentnumber=10\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|class=Senior\n|major=Biology \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1998|3|10|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Eugene, Oregon]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=6\n|weight_lb=237\n|highschool=[[Sheldon High School (Oregon)|Sheldon]] ([[Eugene, Oregon]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (2016\u20132019)\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2017 Las Vegas Bowl]]\n*[[2018 Redbox Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Rose Bowl]] (Offensive MVP)\n*[[2020 Senior Bowl]] (MVP)\n|highlights= *1st Team Pac-12 Academic All-Conference (2017)\n* 1st Team Academic All American (2017)\n* [[Pacific-12 Football Championship Game|Pac-12 champion]] ([[2019 Pac-12 Championship Game|2019]])\n* [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl champion]] ([[2020 Rose Bowl|2020]])\n* [[William V. Campbell Trophy]] (2019)\n|espn=4038941\n|image=Justin_Herbert.png\n}}\n\n'''Justin Herbert''' (born March 10, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon Ducks]].\n\n==Early years==\n\nHerbert, born March 10, 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/pac12/post/_/id/106451/justin-herbert-balances-life-as-the-pac-12s-baby-faced-qb|title=Oregon's Justin Herbert adjusting to life as the Pac-12's baby-faced QB|author=Jennings, Chantel|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> attended [[Sheldon High School (Eugene, Oregon)|Sheldon High School]] in [[Eugene, Oregon]] where he lettered in varsity football, basketball, and baseball. As a senior, he passed for 3,130 yards and 37 touchdowns with 543 rushing yards and 10 rushing touchdowns <ref>{{cite web|url=http://registerguard.com/rg/sports/34464499-81/r-gs-prep-athlete-of-the-year-sheldons-justin-herbert-adds-to-his-familys-legacy-in-three-sports.html.csp|title=The Register-Guard Prep Boys Athlete of the Year: Sheldon\u2019s Justin Herbert adds to his family\u2019s legacy in three sports|publisher=}}</ref> and was named 1st Team All-State<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://mailtribune.com/sports/preps/south-north-players-receive-swc-awards|title=South, North players receive SWC awards|first=Staff|last=reports|publisher=}}</ref> and the Southwest Conference Offensive Player of the Year.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Herbert grew up 10 minutes from [[Autzen Stadium]] and has been a Duck fan since he was a child. His grandfather, Rich Schwab, played receiver at Oregon in the 1960s.<ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/24726591/oregon-ducks-justin-herbert-garnering-heisman-trophy-nfl-draft-buzz|title=If you haven't seen Oregon QB Justin Herbert yet, you're missing out|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHerbert suffered a broken leg in the third game of his junior season at Eugene's Sheldon High School. His broken leg complicated his recruitment process and initially no major programs offered a scholarship as a result. [[Northern Arizona University|Northern Arizona]], [[Portland State University|Portland State]], and [[Montana State University|Montana State]] all extended offers before Nevada and Oregon followed up with his only [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] offers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/uw-husky-football/how-the-huskies-interest-in-an-unknown-justin-herbert-nudged-the-qb-to-rival-oregon/|title=How the Huskies\u2019 interest in an unknown Justin Herbert nudged the QB to rival Oregon|date=October 10, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Herbert committed to his hometown Ducks on October 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/player/_/id/216696/justin-herbert|title=Justin Herbert - Football Recruiting - Player Profiles - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===2016 season===\nEntering his true freshman season listed as QB2 on the depth chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/index.ssf/2016/08/dakota_prukop_named_oregon_duc.html|title=Dakota Prukop named Oregon Ducks starting quarterback, Justin Herbert is the backup|publisher=}}</ref> Herbert became the first true freshman at Oregon to start at Quarterback since [[Chris Miller (American football)|Chris Miller]] in 1983 when the Ducks took on arch-rival Washington on October 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/index.ssf/2016/10/oregon_ducks_list_justin_herbe.html|title=Oregon Ducks list Justin Herbert as starter against Washington|publisher=}}</ref> Despite setting or equaling Oregon's single-game records for total offensive yards (512), passing yards (489), and touchdown passes (6),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://goducks.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=7948|title=Justin Herbert - 2018 Football Roster - GoDucks.com - The University of Oregon Official Athletics Web Site|website=goducks.com}}</ref> the Ducks finished with their worst season in 25 years, going 4\u20138 and failing to make a bowl game for the first time in over a decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lagrandeobserver.com/sports/4859683-151/ducks-fire-helfrich-after-worst-season-in-25|title=Ducks fire Helfrich after worst season in 25 years|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHerbert became the starting quarterback after the fifth game of the season and showcased his talents throwing for 1,936 yards including 19 touchdowns with just four interceptions in eight starts and led a come-from-behind upset at #11 Utah with four touchdowns in the final 15:27 of the game to overcome a 14\u20133 deficit. On the final drive, he completed 6-of-9 passes for 63 yards with a 17-yard game-winning TD pass with two seconds left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/f4d9f132d17e476087268807ae111ee1|title=Oregon upsets No. 11 Utah 30\u201328 on late Carrington TD catch|date=November 20, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\nThe Ducks entered the 2017 season with a new head coach [[Willie Taggart]] after Oregon fired [[Mark Helfrich (American football)|Mark Helfrich]] following the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/oregon-ducks/source-oregon-name-willie-taggart-new-head-football-coach|title=Source: Oregon to name Willie Taggart new head football coach|date=December 6, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Leading the Ducks to a 4\u20131 start, Herbert's transition from the [[Chip Kelly]]/Mark Helfrich era \u201cBlur Offense\u201d to Taggart's \u201cGulf Coast Offense\u201d was successful before he fractured his collarbone against Cal on September 30, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/10/01/oregon-qb-justin-herbert-out-indefinitely-broken-collarbone|title=Oregon QB Justin Herbert expected back in '17|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWithout Herbert in the lineup, the Ducks dropped four of their next five games, and the offense went from averaging 49.2 points per game to just 15.0 points per game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oregon/Bolt/We-break-down-who-Oregon-QBs-fared-during-the-2018-season-112755647/|title=Oregon Positions in Review: Quarterback|publisher=}}</ref> Herbert returned to help the Ducks win their last two regular season games to become bowl eligible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.addictedtoquack.com/2017/11/25/16700318/game-recap-oregon-humiliates-oregon-state-69-10-for-largest-margin-of-victory-in-civil-war-history|title=Game Recap: Oregon humiliates Oregon State 69\u201310 for largest margin of victory in Civil War history|publisher=}}</ref> The Ducks were selected to play [[Boise state football|Boise State]] in the [[2017 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]] but their performance fell flat and the Ducks lost 38\u201328 after head coach Willie Taggart left the team to become the head coach at [[Florida State football|Florida State]] a week before their bowl game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/12/05/willie-taggart-florida-state-oregon-contract|title=Florida State hires Willie Taggart as next coach|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/sports/oregonian/john_canzano/index.ssf/2017/12/canzano_las_vegas_bowl_didnt_m.html|title=Canzano: Las Vegas Bowl didn't matter to the Oregon Ducks... and it showed in loss|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 8 starts, Herbert had a 6\u20132 record and threw for 1,983 yards on 139-of-206 passing attempts (67.5%), including 15 touchdowns against only five interceptions. He also rushed the ball 44 times for 183 yards and five touchdowns.<ref name=\"Justin Herbert\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/player/_/id/4038941/justin-herbert|title=Justin Herbert|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Herbert was named first-team CoSIDA Academic All-American with a 4.08 grade-point average in biology.<ref name=\"goducks.com\">{{cite web|url=https://goducks.com/news/2017/12/14/football-herbert-earns-first-team-academic-all-american-honors.aspx|title=Herbert earns first-team Academic All-America honors - GoDucks.com - The University of Oregon Official Athletics Web Site|website=GoDucks.com - The University of Oregon Official Athletics Web Site}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\nHerbert entered his third collegiate season as an early [[Heisman Trophy]] candidate despite being coached by a third different head coach as well as navigating his third different offensive scheme with new head coach [[Mario Cristobal]] transitioning from the [[spread offense]] to the [[pistol offense]].<ref name=\"espn.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oregon/Article/Oregon-Ducks-running-backs-coach-Jim-Mastro-helped-develop-the-pistol-offense-at-Nevada-117435797/|title=Mastro: Pistol offense 'brings a lot to the table'|publisher=}}</ref> Herbert led the Ducks to a 9\u20134 record and a victory in the [[2018 Redbox Bowl|Redbox Bowl]]. He finished the year with 3,151 passing yards, 29 passing touchdowns, and two rushing touchdowns. His 31 total touchdowns were good for second in the [[Pac-12 Conference]] behind Washington State's [[Gardner Minshew]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/conferences/pac-12/2018.html|title=2018 Pacific-12 Conference Year Summary|website=Sports-Reference.com|access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> He was named to the Pac-12 All-Academic first-team.<ref name=\"2018 all-academic\">{{cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/article/2018/12/02/pac-12-announces-football-all-academic-teams|title=Pac-12 Announces Football All-Academic Teams|work=Pac-12 Conference|date=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nOn December 26, 2018, Herbert announced that he would return to Oregon for his senior season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Justin Herbert decides to stay at Oregon for senior season and bypass NFL draft|author=Gleeson, Scott|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/pac12/2018/12/26/justin-herbert-passes-nfl-draft-stay-oregon-senior-season/2415263002/|date=December 26, 2018|accessdate=January 12, 2018|work=USA Toay}}</ref> He led his team to a 12-2 record and to a win in the [[2020 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]], in which he won the Offensive MVP award. In addition to his on-field success, Herbert was named the 30th recipient of [[William_V._Campbell_Trophy|The William V. Cambell Trophy]]. For winning this award, which is referred to as the \"Academic Heisman,\" Herbert was honored during the 2020 College Football Playoff National Title Game.<ref>https://247sports.com/college/oregon/Article/Justin-Herbert-Oregon-Ducks-Football-Rose-Bowl-NFL-CFP-title--141685854/</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{|style=\"cellpadding=1; text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Oregon Ducks}};\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | || colspan=\"9\" | Passing || colspan=\"4\" | Rushing\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Oregon Ducks}};\"\n| Season || Team || W-L || COMP || ATT || PCT || YDS || YDS/A || TD || INT || [[Passer rating|<span style=\"color:#FFCC00;\">RAT</span>]] || [[Total quarterback rating|<span style=\"color:#FFCC00;\">QBR</span>]] || ATT || YDS || YDS/A || TD\n|-\n| [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS footbal